SIMPLE: speech
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Speech
<hw>Speech</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>speche</ets>,
AS. <ets>sp<?/c</ets>, <ets>spr<?/</ets>, fr. <ets>specan</ets>,
<ets>sprecan</ets>, to speak; akin to D. <ets>spraak</ets> speech, OHG.
<ets>spr⟦amac⟧hha</ets>, G. <ets>sprache</ets>, Sw. <ets>spr<?/k</ets>,
Dan. <ets>sprog</ets>. See <er>Speak</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The
faculty of uttering articulate sounds or words; the faculty of
expressing thoughts by words or articulate sounds; the power of
speaking.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There is none comparable to the variety of instructive expressions
by <qex>speech</qex>, wherewith man alone is endowed for the
communication of his thoughts.</q> <rj><qau>Holder.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>he act of speaking; that which is spoken; words, as
expressing ideas; language; conversation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Speech is voice modulated by the throat, tongue, lips,
etc., the modulation being accomplished by changing the form of the
cavity of the mouth and nose through the action of muscles which move
their walls.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>O goode God! how gentle and how kind⟦br⟧
Ye seemed by your <qex>speech</qex> and your visage⟦br⟧
The day that maked was our marriage.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The acts of God . . . to human ears⟦br⟧
Can nort without process of <qex>speech</qex> be told.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A particular language, as distinct from others; a
tongue; a dialect.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>People of a strange <qex>speech</qex> and of an hard language.</q>
<rj><qau>Ezek. iii. 6.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Talk; mention; common saying.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The duke . . . did of me demand⟦br⟧
What was the <qex>speech</qex> among the Londoners⟦br⟧
Concerning the French journey.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>formal discourse in public; oration;
harangue.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The constant design of these orators, in all their
<qex>speeches</qex>, was to drive some one particular point.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Any declaration of thoughts.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I. with leave of <qex>speech</qex> implored, . . . replied.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> Harangue; language; address; oration. See
<er>Harangue</er>, and <er>Language</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Speech</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Speech
<hw>Speech</hw>, <pos>v. i. & t.</pos> <def>To make a speech; to
harangue.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Speechful</ent>⟦br⟧
